post_text: Okay Ansley students, I've really enjoyed the weather the last couple days and I hope you have too. I'm going to give you a challenge. This is the Andy Goldsworthy Challenge. He is a British sculptor and photographer. He uses inspiration from nature to create beautiful images. I want to encourage you to go outside and create a unique scene from nature, photograph it and then post it. I've created a very short Google Slides to show you some of his work. Have fun! https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1npwIOEIckZhq-z5kwNo5hTJ7kazafBvICgxux8QIpmc/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
Congratulations to Maysa Jones and Mayra Sanchez for having their artwork selected to represent Ansley Elementary at the Nebraska State Capital during the Youth Art Month Art Show. Their pieces will be displayed March 9-21.

Maysa created a Mixed Media cactus drawing using construction paper crayons, watercolor pencils, and watercolors. Her work is titled “Wild Cactus”

Mayra created a current event inspired piece called “Endangered Koala” to represent recent wildfires in Australia . It was created with markers and model magic.

Congratulations girls!

post_text: Mr. Helberg set up a wonderful opportunity for our juniors and seniors. Today we were able to view the art exhibit of Samuel Bak on display at UNO. Bak is a halocuast survivor and has dedicated his life to telling his story through art. The students learned about all the hidden symbols in his work and how it represents the lives of so many Jewish families during WWII. This exhibit is powerful and emotional. If you have a chance to view it please do. Please ask our students to share their thoughts on the show! Thank you Mr. Helberg for arranging this trip.

post_text: Thank you to ALL who took the time to enjoy the art show tonight! The kids have worked so hard this year and it goes without saying that I'm so very proud of them! Tonight wasn't possible without the help of many volunteers. My high school students helped sort, tag and hang over 500 pieces of art without complaining! Cortnee Eberle even donated her time tonight to help sell tshirts. Mrs. Smith and Mr. Olson donated their free time this weekend to haul in and set up the panels with very minimal complaining! 😉 Mrs. Cash has been working diligently every day since January to catalog all of the artwork on Artsonia. And our staff and administration for supporting the visual and performing arts! Art can bring us together and I'm so thankful I'm a part of this community!

post_text: Good morning elementary parents! I would like to share some awesome news with you. All year long Mrs. Cash and I (mostly Mrs. Cash) have been working hard to upload photos of your students artwork. We are using an online program called Artsonia. This allows you to view the artwork your student has created and to buy items with the image on it. The best part of this program is that you can watch your child's talents grow through the years. It cost nothing to join! I will have log-in information for your child at the Spring Concert and Art Show on April 9th. www.artsonia.com

post_text: Today my 6th graders blew me away. I had planned a two part lesson about tessellations. The first part involved a quick intro using an online tessellation generator that creates instant patterns. However, these kids ran away with the first part that we didnt even get to the second part. In fact they left 15 minutes later than scheduled to keep playing and making designs. They were so creative and really impressed me. #math #art.

post_text: Congratulations Hannah Speer and Tiffany Wooters! Their pieces were selected for a Scolastics Art Award and show held in Omaha. Over 3,800 high school art pieces from across the state of Nebraska were entered with only 36% making the show. Hannah recieved a Silver Key Award for her watercolor painting called "The City". Tiffany received an Honerable Mention for her acrylic self portrait titled "Tiffany". Congratulations, I'm proud of you both!

post_text: Ansley and Litchfield teamed up for a fantastic spARTan field trip! We started the day with Icon Poly and learned about molding and casting. Next was on to local artist Beth Jasnoch's metal studio. Finally we learned about the screenprint process. Some students even pulled their own shirt. This was a great day and we walked away with some great experiences and memories. Thank you Mrs. Varah, Art Litchfield, and your students for making this such a fun trip!
